xxl.core.cursors.filters

Class Dropper<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • xxl.core.cursors.SecureDecoratorCursor<E>
      • xxl.core.cursors.filters.Dropper<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of the elements returned by this iteration.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterator<E>, Cursor<E>

    public class Dropper<E>
extends SecureDecoratorCursor<E>
    A dropper drops a user defined number of the given iterator's elements. The implementation of the method drop is as follows: 
       while (number-->0 && super.hasNext());
       super.next();
    The first number elements are removed from the wrapped iteration, because the next method is callednumber times.

    Example usage: 

       Dropper<Integer> dropper = new Dropper<Integer>(new Enumerator(11), 5);
   
   dropper.open();
   
   while(dropper.hasNext())
       System.out.println(dropper.next());
       
   dropper.close();
    This example creates a new dropper by using an enumerator delivering integer elements from 0 to 10, where the first five elements are dropped. Therefore the generated output is: 
         5
     6
     7
     8
     9
     10

    See Also:
    Iterator, Cursor, SecureDecoratorCursor

      • open

        public void open()
        Opens the cursor, i.e., signals the cursor to reserve resources, open files, etc. Before a cursor has been opened calls to methods like next or peek are not guaranteed to yield proper results. Therefore open must be called before a cursor's data can be processed. Multiple calls to open do not have any effect, i.e., if open was called the cursor remains in the state opened until its close method is called.

        Note, that a call to the open method of a closed cursor usually does not open it again because of the fact that its state generally cannot be restored when resources are released respectively files are closed.

        Specified by:
        open in interface Cursor<E>
        Overrides:
        open in class SecureDecoratorCursor<E>

      • reset

        public void reset()
           throws UnsupportedOperationException
        Resets the cursor to its initial state such that the caller is able to traverse the underlying data structure again without constructing a new cursor (optional operation). The modifications, removes and updates concerning the underlying data structure, are still persistent.

        Note, that this operation is optional and does not work for this cursor.

        Specified by:
        reset in interface Cursor<E>
        Overrides:
        reset in class SecureDecoratorCursor<E>
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the reset operation is not supported by the cursor.
